SP  - 527
EP  - 534
VL  - 39
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb02325.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT In this paper a systematic procedure is developed to determine necessary conditions for all degrees of stochastic dominance. The previously known necessary conditions are specified as to which degrees of dominance they belong, and two new necessary conditions, a ranking of harmonic means and a ranking of algebraic combinations of the first three moments, are derived.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Municipal Bond Demand Premiums and Bond Price Volatility: A Note
AU  - STOCK, DUANE
AU  - SCHREMS, EDWARD L.
Y1  - 1984/06/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb02326.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 535
EP  - 539
VL  - 39
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb02326.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT The behavior of different components of municipal bond yields may have a significant impact upon bond price behavior. Specifically, demand premiums created by banks may stabilize bond yields in some maturity ranges but not in others; for example, short-term municipals may be stabilized but not long-term. This research implies that bank demand behavior may create demand premiums that stabilize prices of short-term municipal bonds relative to those of Treasury bonds of like maturity. While this implication is inconsistent with the residual theory of bank demand, it is consistent with the tax-shield theory attributed to Hendershott and Koch [3, 4].
ER  - 

